ial Williamsburg Foundation", "accessdate": "2008-04-12", "author": "Hellier, Cathy"} Block discovered that the first recorded game of "Bass-Ball" took place in 1749 in Surrey, and featured the Prince of Wales as a player.{"citetype": "news", "date": "2013-07-26", "title": "Why isn't baseball more popular in the UK?", "url": "https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-23425907", "work": "BBC News", "accessdate": "26 July 2013"} This early form of the game was apparently brought to Canada by English immigrants.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://boston.redsox.mlb.com/NASApp/mlb/news/article.jsp?ymd=20050802&content_id=1154441&vkey=news_bos&fext=.jsp&c_id=bos", "title": "Pittsfield: Small City, Big Baseball Town", "date": "August 2, 2005", "publisher": "Major League Baseball", "accessdate": "2009-02-03", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20060321043321/http://boston.redsox.mlb.com/NASApp/mlb/news/article.jsp?ymd=20050802&content_id=1154441&vkey=news_bos&fext=.jsp&c_id=bos", "archivedate": "March 21, 2006", "author": "Miller, Doug", "df": "mdy-all"}
By the early 1830s, there were reports of a variety of uncodified bat-and-ball games recognizable as early forms of baseball being played around North America.[48] The first officially recorded baseball game on this continent was played in Beachville, Ontario, Canada, on June 4, 1838.{"citetype": "news", "date": "June 15, 2017", "title": "How Canada invented 'American' football, baseball, basketball and hockey", "url": "https://www.cbc.ca/sportslongform/entry/how-canada-invented-american-football-baseball-basketball-and-hockey", "language": "en-US", "publisher": "[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]", "accessdate": "June 4, 2019", "last": "Giddens", "first": "David"} In 1845, Alexander Cartwright, a member of New York City's Knickerbocker Club, led the codification of the so-called Knickerbocker Rules.{"citetype": "book", "year": "1997", "title": "Early Innings: A Documentary History of Baseball, 1825\u20131908", "url": "https://archive.org/details/earlyinningsdocu00sull", "publisher": "University of Nebraska Press", "isbn": "978-0-8032-9244-4", "oclc": "36258074", "last": "Sullivan", "first": "Dean (ed.)", "urlaccess": "registration"} While there are reports that the New York Knickerbockers played games in 1845, the contest long recognized as the first officially recorded baseball game in U.S. history took place on June 19, 1846, in Hoboken, New Jersey: the "New York Nine" defeated the Knickerbockers, 23–1, in four innings.[51] With the Knickerbocker code as the basis, the rules of modern baseball continued to evolve over the next half-century.{"citetype": "book", "year": "2000", "title": "Past Time: Baseball as History", "url": "https://archive.org/details/pasttimebaseball0000tygi", "publisher": "Oxford University Press", "isbn": "978-0-19-508958-5", "oclc": "42290019", "last": "Tygiel", "first": "Jules", "urlaccess": "registration"}

Establishment of professional leagues
In the mid-1850s, a baseball craze hit the New York metropolitan area,[53] and by 1856, local journals were referring to baseball as the "national pastime" or "national game".[54] A year later, the sport's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players, was formed. In 1867, it barred participation by African Americans.[55] The more formally structured National League was founded in 1876.[56] Professional Negro leagues formed, but quickly folded.[57] In 1887, softball, under the name of indoor baseball or indoor-outdoor, was invented as a winter version of the parent game.[58] The National League's first successful counterpart, the American League, which evolved from the minor Western League, was established in 1893, and virtually all of the modern baseball rules were in place by then.[59][60]
The National Agreement of 1903 formalized relations both between the two major leagues and between them and the National Association of Professional Base Ball Leagues, representing most of the country's minor professional leagues.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://roadsidephotos.sabr.org/baseball/1903NatAgree.htm", "title": "National Agreement for the Government of Professional Base Ball Clubs", "publisher": "roadsidephotos.sabr.org", "accessdate": "2009-01-29"} The World Series, pitting the two major league champions against each other, was inaugurated that fall.[62]  The Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series led to the formation of a new National Commission of baseball that drew the two major leagues closer together.{"citetype": "book", "year": "2003", "title": "The Business of Baseball", "publisher": "McFarland", "isbn": "978-0-7864-1426-0", "oclc": "50866929", "last": "Powers", "first": "Albert Theodore"} The first major league baseball commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, was elected in 1920. That year also saw the founding of the Negro National League; the first significant Negro league, it would operate until 1931. For part of the 1920s, it was joined by the Eastern Colored League.{"citetype": "book", "year": "2007", "title": "Playing America's Game: Baseball, Latinos, and the Color Line", "url": "https://archive.org/details/playingamericasg00burg", "publisher": "[[University of California Press]]", "isbn": "978-0-520-25143-4", "oclc": "81150202", "last": "Burgos", "first": "Adrian", "urlaccess": "registration"}

Rise of Ruth and racial integration
Compared with the present, professional baseball in the early 20th century was lower-scoring, and pitchers were more dominant.[65] The so-called dead-ball era ended in the early 1920s with several changes in rule and circumstance that were advantageous to hitters. Strict new regulations governed the ball's size, shape and composition, along with a new rule officially banning the spitball and other pitches that depended on the ball being treated or roughed-up with foreign substances, resulted in a ball that traveled farther when hit.[66] The rise of the legendary player Babe Ruth, the first great power hitter of the new era, helped permanently alter the nature of the game.[67] In the late 1920s and early 1930s, St. Louis Cardinals general manager Branch Rickey invested in several minor league clubs and developed the first modern farm system.{"citetype": "book", "year": "2001", "title": "Never Just a Game: Players, Owners, and American Baseball to 1920", "publisher": "[[University of North Carolina Press]]", "isbn": "978-0-8078-4961-3", "oclc": "28183874", "last": "Burk", "first": "Robert F."} A new Negro National League was organized in 1933; four years later, it was joined by the Negro American League. The first elections to the National Baseball Hall of Fame took place in 1936. In 1939, Little League Baseball was founded in Pennsylvania.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.littleleague.org/about/history.asp", "title": "History of Little League", "publisher": "Little League", "accessdate": "2007-06-26", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20070514082459/http://www.littleleague.org/about/history.asp", "archivedate": "2007-05-14"}
A large number of minor league teams disbanded when World War II led to a player shortage. Chicago Cubs owner Philip K. Wrigley led the formation of the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League to help keep the game in the public eye.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.aagpbl.org/index.cfm/pages/league/12/league-history", "title": "League History", "year": "2005", "publisher": "All-American Girls Professional Baseball League Players Association", "accessdate": "2009-01-29", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20110724213445/http://aagpbl.org/index.cfm/pages/league/12/league-history", "archivedate": "July 24, 2011", "author": "Lesko, Jeneane", "df": "mdy-all"} The first crack in the unwritten agreement barring blacks from white-controlled professional ball occurred in 1945: Jackie Robinson was signed by the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and began playing for their minor league team in Montreal.[71] In 1947, Robinson broke the major leagues' color barrier when he debuted with the Dodgers.[72] Latin American players, largely overlooked before, also started entering the majors in greater numbers. In 1951, two Chicago White Sox, Venezuelan-born Chico Carrasquel and black Cuban-born Minnie Miñoso, became the first Hispanic All-Stars.[73]{"citetype": "news", "date": "October 26, 2005", "title": "Baseball: White Sox and Fans Speak Same Language, with a Spanish Accent", "url": "https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E06E3DD113FF935A15753C1A9639C8B63", "work": "[[The New York Times]]", "accessdate": "2009-02-04"} Integration proceeded slowly: by 1953, only six of the 16 major league teams had a black player on the roster.[73]

Attendance records and the age of steroids
In 1975, the union's power—and players' salaries—began to increase greatly when the reserve clause was effectively struck down, leading to the free agency system.[75] Significant work stoppages occurred in 1981 and 1994, the latter forcing the cancellation of the World Series for the first time in 90 years.[76] Attendance had been growing steadily since the mid-1970s and in 1994, before the stoppage, the majors were setting their all-time record for per-game attendance.{"citetype": "book", "year": "2006", "title": "Baseball Without Borders: The International Pastime", "publisher": "University of Nebraska Press", "isbn": "978-0-8032-7125-8", "oclc": "64594333", "last": "Gmelch", "first": "George"}{"citetype": "book", "year": "2004", "title": "Koppett's Concise History of Major League Baseball", "publisher": "[[Carroll & Graf Publishers|Carroll & Graf]]", "isbn": "978-0-7867-1286-1", "oclc": "54674804", "last": "Koppett", "first": "Leonard"} After play resumed in 1995, non-division-winning wild card teams became a permanent fixture of the post-season. Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997 and the second-highest attendance mark for a full season was set.[79] In 2000, the National and American Leagues were dissolved as legal entities. While their identities were maintained for scheduling purposes (and the designated hitter distinction), the regulations and other functions—such as player discipline and umpire supervision—they had administered separately were consolidated under the rubric of MLB.[80]
In 2001, Barry Bonds established the current record of 73 home runs in a single season. There had long been suspicions that the dramatic increase in power hitting was fueled in large part by the abuse of illegal steroids (as well as by the dilution of pitching talent due to expansion), but the issue only began attracting significant media attention in 2002 and there was no penalty for the use of performance-enhancing drugs before 2004.{"citetype": "news", "date": "May 29, 2012", "title": "To Cheat or Not to Cheat", "url": "http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/magazine/05/29/baseball.steroids/index.html", "work": "[[Sports Illustrated]]", "accessdate": "2012-05-30", "author": "Verducci, Tom"} In 2007, Bonds became MLB's all-time home run leader, surpassing Hank Aaron, as total major league and minor league attendance both reached all-time highs.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/article/124427", "title": "MLB Regular-Season Attendance Just Shy of Last Year's Record", "accessdate": "2009-01-29", "work": "Street & Smith's SportsBusiness Daily"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://web.minorleaguebaseball.com/milb/history/", "title": "Minor League Baseball History", "publisher": "Minor League Baseball", "accessdate": "2009-01-29", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20090120173052/http://web.minorleaguebaseball.com/milb/history/", "archivedate": "January 20, 2009", "df": "mdy-all"}

Around the world
