Popularity and cultural impact
Writing in 1919, philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen described baseball as America's national religion.[142] In the words of sports columnist Jayson Stark, baseball has long been "a unique paragon of American culture"—a status he sees as devastated by the steroid abuse scandal.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/columns/story?columnist=stark_jayson&id=3892788", "title": "A-Rod Has Destroyed Game's History", "date": "February 8, 2009", "publisher": "[[ESPN.com]]", "accessdate": "2009-02-08", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20090210124048/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/columns/story?columnist=stark_jayson&id=3892788", "archivedate": "February 10, 2009", "author": "Stark, Jayson"} Baseball has an important place in other national cultures as well: Scholar Peter Bjarkman describes "how deeply the sport is ingrained in the history and culture of a nation such as Cuba, [and] how thoroughly it was radically reshaped and nativized in Japan."[144] Since the early 1980s, the Dominican Republic, in particular the city of San Pedro de Macorís, has been the major leagues' primary source of foreign talent.[145] In 2017, 83 of the 868 players on MLB Opening Day rosters (and disabled lists) were from the country. Among other Caribbean countries and territories, a combined 97 MLB players were born in Venezuela, Cuba, and Puerto Rico.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-day-rosters-feature-230-players-born-outside-the-us/c-116591920", "title": "Opening Day Rosters Feature 230 Players Born Outside the U.S.", "publisher": "Major League Baseball", "accessdate": "April 24, 2018"} Hall-of-Famer Roberto Clemente remains one of the greatest national heroes in Puerto Rico's history.[147] While baseball has long been the island's primary athletic pastime, its once well-attended professional winter league has declined in popularity since 1990, when young Puerto Rican players began to be included in the major leagues' annual first-year player draft.{"citetype": "news", "date": "January 16, 2012", "title": "Puerto Rico Traces Baseball's Slide to the Draft", "url": "https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/17/sports/baseball/puerto-rico-traces-decline-in-prospects-to-inclusion-in-the-baseball-draft.html", "work": "The New York Times", "accessdate": "2012-01-25", "author": "Castillo, Jorge"} In Asia, baseball is among the most popular sports in Japan and South Korea.{"citetype": "news", "date": "March 21, 2017", "title": "World Baseball Classic keeps sport relevant in Japan", "url": "http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-us-japan-hernandez-20170321-story.html", "work": "Los Angeles Times", "accessdate": "2018-04-26", "author": "Hernandez, Dylan"}
The major league game in the United States was originally targeted toward a middle-class, white-collar audience: relative to other spectator pastimes, the National League's set ticket price of 50 cents in 1876 was high, while the location of playing fields outside the inner city and the workweek daytime scheduling of games were also obstacles to a blue-collar audience.[150] A century later, the situation was very different. With the rise in popularity of other team sports with much higher average ticket prices—football, basketball, and hockey—professional baseball had become among the most blue-collar-oriented of leading American spectator sports.[151]
Overall, baseball has a large following in the United States; a 2006 poll found that nearly half of Americans are fans.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://news.gallup.com/poll/22240/nearly-half-americans-baseball-fans.aspx", "title": "Nearly Half of Americans are Baseball Fans", "last": "Jones", "first": "Jeffrey M.", "date": "April 4, 2006", "publisher": "Gallup", "accessdate": "May 31, 2018"} In the late 1900s and early 2000s, baseball's position compared to football in the United States moved in contradictory directions. In 2008, MLB set a revenue record of $6.5 billion, matching the NFL's revenue for the first time in decades.{"citetype": "news", "date": "October 1, 2008", "title": "Major League Baseball Revenue Reaches Record, Attendance Falls", "url": "https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=asFEMjfiKA5s", "urlstatus": "dead", "publisher": "Bloomberg.com", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20110629051650/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=asFEMjfiKA5s", "archivedate": "June 29, 2011", "accessdate": "2009-02-08", "author": "Kercheval, Nancy", "df": "mdy-all"} A new MLB revenue record of more than $10 billion was set in 2017.{"citetype": "news", "date": "November 22, 2017", "title": "Report: MLB revenues exceed $10 billion for the first time", "url": "https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/2017/11/22/mlb-revenues-exceed-10-billion/890041001/", "work": "USA Today", "accessdate": "March 27, 2018"} On the other hand, the percentage of American sports fans polled who named baseball as their favorite sport was 9%, compared to pro football at 37%.{"citetype": "news", "date": "January 10, 2018", "title": "Despite all the bad news, poll shows football still is America's favorite sport by a wide margin", "url": "https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2018/01/10/despite-all-the-bad-news-poll-shows-football-still-is-americas-favorite-sport-by-a-wide-margin/", "work": "The Washington Post", "accessdate": "March 27, 2018", "last": "Bonesteel", "first": "Matt"} In 1985, the respective figures were pro football 24%, baseball 23%.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.allbusiness.com/sports-recreation/sports-games-outdoor/11762627-1.html", "title": "Professional Football Continues Dominance over Baseball as America's Favorite Sport", "date": "January 27, 2009", "publisher": "AllBusiness", "accessdate": "2010-09-15", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20110110073300/http://www.allbusiness.com/sports-recreation/sports-games-outdoor/11762627-1.html", "archivedate": "2011-01-10", "work": "Business Wire"} Because there are so many more major league games played, there is no comparison in overall attendance.{"citetype": "news", "date": "April 10, 2015", "title": "Popularity Contest: Baseball vs. Football", "url": "https://www.wsj.com/articles/popularity-contest-baseball-vs-football-1428679449", "work": "The Wall Street Journal", "accessdate": "2018-05-18", "last": "McGinty", "first": "Jo Craven", "urlaccess": "subscription"} In 2008, total attendance at major league games was the second-highest in history: 78.6 million, 0.7% off the record set the previous year.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/article/124427", "title": "MLB Regular-Season Attendance Just Shy of Last Year's Record", "accessdate": "2009-01-29", "work": "Street & Smith's SportsBusiness Daily"} The following year, amid the U.S. recession, attendance fell by 6.6% to 73.4 million.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.bizofbaseball.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4124:mlb-sees-a-record-66-billion-in-revenues-for-2009&catid=30:mlb-news&Itemid=42", "title": "MLB Sees a Record $6.6 Billion in Revenues for 2009", "date": "February 25, 2010", "publisher": "Biz of Baseball", "accessdate": "2010-09-17", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20101027080204/http://bizofbaseball.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4124%3Amlb-sees-a-record-66-billion-in-revenues-for-2009&catid=30%3Amlb-news&Itemid=42", "archivedate": "October 27, 2010", "author": "Brown, Maury", "df": "mdy-all"} Eight years later, it dropped under 73 million.{"citetype": "news", "date": "April 16, 2018", "title": "10 Degrees: MLB's enormous attendance drop due to bad weather or something far worse for baseball?", "url": "https://sports.yahoo.com/10-degrees-mlbs-enormous-attendance-drop-due-bad-weather-something-far-worse-baseball-152051024.html", "work": "Yahoo Sports", "accessdate": "2018-06-16", "author": "Jeff Passan"} Attendance at games held under the Minor League Baseball umbrella set a record in 2008, with 43.3 million.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.milb.com/milb/news/minor-league-attendance-tops-425-million/c-148297748", "title": "Minor League attendance tops 42.5 million", "date": "September 9, 2015", "publisher": "Minor League Baseball", "accessdate": "2018-06-16"} While MLB games have not drawn the same national TV viewership as football games, MLB games are dominant in teams' local markets and regularly lead all programs in primetime in their markets during the summer.[161]
In Japan, where baseball is inarguably the leading spectator team sport, combined revenue for the twelve teams in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the body that oversees both the Central and Pacific Leagues, was estimated at $1 billion in 2007. Total NPB attendance for the year was approximately 20 million. While in the preceding two decades, MLB attendance grew by 50 percent and revenue nearly tripled, the comparable NPB figures were stagnant. There are concerns that MLB's growing interest in acquiring star Japanese players will hurt the game in their home country.{"citetype": "news", "date": "April 11, 2007", "title": "Is the MLB Destroying Japan's National Pastime?", "url": "http://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2007/04/11/baseball/is-the-mlb-destroying-japans-national-pastime/", "work": "[[The Japan Times]]", "accessdate": "2009-02-08", "author": "Whiting, Robert"} In Cuba, where baseball is by every reckoning the national sport,{"citetype": "book", "year": "2001", "title": "The Pride of Havana: A History of Cuban Baseball", "publisher": "[[Oxford University Press]]", "isbn": "978-0-19-514605-9", "oclc": "46601626", "last": "Gonz\u00e1lez Echevarr\u00eda", "first": "Roberto"} the national team overshadows the city and provincial teams that play in the top-level domestic leagues.{"citetype": "news", "date": "March 5, 2009", "title": "Cubans' Baseball Dreams Take Root on Rocky Fields", "url": "https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/2009-03-05-3277668016_x.htm", "work": "USA Today", "agency": "Associated Press", "accessdate": "2009-04-28", "author": "Weissert, Will"} Revenue figures are not released for the country's amateur system. Similarly, according to one official pronouncement, the sport's governing authority "has never taken into account attendance ... because its greatest interest has always been the development of athletes".[165]
